tweet: 13/ I wrote an article about it here.  It's not inflation, it's how a few people at the Fed think about inflation.   https://t.co/x53StrRKzo
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 12/ Negative correlation over the last 20 years is a oddity in history.  It was only present because of the fear of deflation.  The same applies in reverse. If the Fed didn't care about inflation (and it doesn't need to, it's only accepted theory), then the outcome would change.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 11/ If there never was recession, you wouldn't bother holding bonds in your portfolio.  Similarly, if the Fed didn't ever care about inflation, they would cut in every recession, forcing the negative correlation to persist for all of history.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 10/ 60/40 portfolios work purely due to this change in correlation. When equities are falling and there is panic, bonds kick in and support the portfolio.  On the way out they detract, but not as much as equities recover.  Otherwise they add. The perfect hedge.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 9/ It is ONLY this recessionary environment (and the subsequent recovery) that mathematically creates negative correlation.  As we know, equities and bonds, in normal times, both return positively, meaning the correlation naturally changes.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 8/ If the goals aren't aligned, then the Fed won't cut, and bonds don't benefit from huge gains in that environment.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 7/ The language is so important because it tells us what the Fed will do and how aggressively it will do it in an economic downturn.  If deflation is the worry, there is no limit to how far the Fed will cut as the two goals (employment and inflation) are aligned to the same side.
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 6/ Finally, in 2003, it turned to this:  "The risk of inflation becoming desirably low would remain the predominant concern".  Negative correlation was then born. Only when the Fed told us it would. Nothing to do with actual inflation itself.  https://t.co/P106tabC9Q
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 5/ This started the "no correlation" period of 1997-2002.  The chart below shows the "transition period" for bond-equity correlation.  https://t.co/c7IbjIbQnq
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 4/ This language continued throughout the '90s. The PTSD of the '70s episode hadn't left the Fed for decades after.  But this changed in 1998. All of a sudden, the Fed saw the risk move from higher inflation, to deflation. It took 5 or 6 years of 2.5% inflation to get them there.  https://t.co/rtVRjycf0W
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 3/ It was this super low inflation that changed how the Fed viewed inflation.  Compare the following Fed minutes extracts.  The first, from 1986, when inflation hit 1.5% (yes 1.5%).  It was about "progress against inflation". Inflation was STILL the risk.  https://t.co/8CDJrJAJOk
name: Count Draghula

tweet: 2/ Bonds were positively correlated from 1967 to 1997 or so.  Also shown by the chart, inflation was below 3% in the measured low inflation period in the '90s.  What changed in 1998? Super low inflation.  https://t.co/s8M6qNrmm7
name: Count Draghula
